</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/11/02 9:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=14.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: GnawAnPis condemns space colonies</span><hr size=1> I just wish for once that I could run across a discussion of this from a humanist perspective, that wasn't basically anti-government, anti technology, and completely anti-space.<br>
<br>
 Sure, I don't want to see global mega-conglomerates own the Moon &amp; asteroids for profit, while the people who aren't major share-holders get nothing. (The old SP slogan: &quot;Do you get the profits from the mine, or do you get the shaft?&quot;)<br>
 There has just got to be a better stance to take than that all technology is evil, that any effort to go to space is part of a sinister Illuminati oil company conspiracy...<br>
<br>
I'm really pissed off at this <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.globenet.free-online.co.uk/articles/scandm.htm">article</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> from the GNAW n PiS site. The 4th paragraph, it mentions &quot;<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0201328194/qid=1018583508/sr=2-1/ref=sr_2_1/103-4869161-3918208">Mining the Sky</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->&quot; by Lewis:<br>
--------------------<br>
In his book Mining the Sky: Untold Riches from the Asteroids, Comets, and Planets, NASA scientist John S. Lewis paints a picture of enormous profits to be made by the nation that controls the territory on the Moon, Mars, or other planetary bodies. These planetary bodies, he maintains, contain the untapped resources and riches of the future. Lewis, going beyond the Columbus mythology says, &quot;…<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The global expansion of European technology and civilization brought about by the terrestrial age of exploration is but a pale foreshadowing of the opportunities before us as humans move out into space</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.&quot;<br>
--------------------<br>
 There's no doubt that they're setting it up for a tirade against Global business/American military/industrial profit hoarding people-squashing hegemony.<br>
<br>
 They miss a few parts in the book. Lewis discusses the immense wealth in space resources (absolutely incredible. Absolutely dwarfs any conception we today have of &quot;riches&quot; or prosperity. The total global economic value isn't a drop in an ocean). He immediately goes on to say that there's no end to the good we could do for the Earth and the Human condition with all this. He argues the case that there's no reason why we can't or shouldn't strive for not only universally <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> adequate</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> standard of living for everyone, but he says we should be thinking of providing universally <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>affluent</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> conditions for everyone alive -and we should be planning to allow for up to hundreds of billions of people someday...<br>
 More than once he writes &quot;<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> It's not only good, sound business acumen, it's the <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>right</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> thing to do</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->&quot;.<br>
<br>
 (I'll dig the book up from a library with 'net connections, and provide specific instances &amp; page numbers with more complete quotes)<br>
<br>
 This is a more complete version of a quote I've reprinted before: I like the way it challenges the entire &quot;conventional wisdom&quot; which says that there are too many of us; that <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>over</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->population is the problem.<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  As long as the human population remains as pitifully small as it is today, we shall be severely limited in what we can accomplish. Human intelligence is the key to the future: human beings are not, as some would have it, a form of pollution.<br>
 Having only one Einstein, one Hokusai, one Mozart, one daVinci, one Shankara,... is not enough. We need -and can have- a million times as many.<br>
